post_text: The William James College INTERFACE Referral Service, offered through our Freedman Center, is an outpatient mental health and wellness referral Helpline available Monday through Friday, 9 am-5 pm, at 888-244-6843 (toll free). This is a free, confidential referral service for residents and public school students of participating communities. Callers from these participating communities are matched with licensed outpatient mental health providers from our extensive database, on average, within 2 weeks of their call to INTERFACE. Each referral best meets the specialty needs, insurance or fee requirement, location and availability needs of the caller. For more information: visit our Facebook page @InterfaceReferralService or our website at interface.williamjames.edu

March 20th at 7:00pm

Tickets $5 for students and seniors and $7 for adults. Tickets available in the KMS office or at the door.

Light breakfast food and drink will be offered.

All after school and evening activities/events for the Natick Public Schools are CLOSED ON DECEMBER 17, 2019 due to the winter weather conditions.

Due to the quickly changing weather patterns and dropping temps, ASAP Staff will remain in the building, however, we ask that you make alternate arrangements for pickup. We understand that not all families will be able to arrive prior to ASAP closing, but we will monitor students until you arrive. Please be sure to update your pickup plans as needed and understand that offices might be overrun with calls at this time.

Athletics and Arts events will be rescheduled. Stay tuned for emails from your advisors.

We appreciate your patience and understanding about this swift decision, it was made in the interest of safety.

Please be safe on the roads.

post_text:
Can you help our students to be empathetic learners, thinkers and problem solvers?

Can you help us instill in them the resiliency skills they'll need to take on adversity and build consensus through teamwork?

If you share our belief, the Natick Public Schools invites you to apply for one or both of the positions below!

Daily Substitute Teacher - Support student achievement in the absence of regular classroom teachers, on a per diem basis. Bachelor degree preferred, but not required if you have relevant experience.

Paraprofessional Educator - Work with students individually and in small groups to implement IEP's. Provide support with academics, and behavioral strategies. Compassion, empathy and experience working with children is required.

If you are unsure whether you meet the qualifications of this position, or how this would be determined, please feel free to talk to one of our hiring administrators, or call Human Resources at 508-647-6495.

Apply TODAY at www.natickps.org/careers

PLEASE NOTE: Concrete floor placements for the Kennedy Building Project are scheduled for tomorrow, Tuesday 11/19.

Potential Impacts:
Efforts will be made to avoid arrival and dismissal times as much as possible. However, the main construction gate could be open during drop-off and pick-up times and concrete trucks could be in school traffic flow. Please use caution.

Efforts will be made to reduce the duration of the concrete floor finishing in order to mitigate disturbances to the surrounding community. At this time, work is not anticipated to extend beyond normal construction hours (7 pm).

Schedule may be subject to change due to weather.

post_text:
We're thrilled to share that Natick was selected to participate in Influence 100!

This is an initiative aimed at increasing the racial and ethnic diversity of superintendents and creating more culturally responsive districts and leaders in order to promote better outcomes for students.

Learn more about this remarkable program and our fellows: http://www.natickps.org/news/current/influence_100_2019

Image Caption: On October 11, DESE kicked off the Influence 100 pilot program (top photo), an initiative aimed at increasing the racial and ethnic diversity of superintendents and creating more culturally responsive districts and leaders in order to promote better outcomes for students. Also that day, DESE began the second cohort of InSPIRED fellows (bottom photo, which includes fellows and district partners)]
